               <!-- /btArticleMedia -->
               <div class="btArticleContent ">
                  <div class="bt_bb_wrapper">
                  <div class="bodytext contentText"> <p>Many of us don’t think about our air conditioner until something goes wrong. However, maintenance is the most effective way to prevent potentially expensive repairs.</p> </div>
                  <div class="bodytext contentText"> <p>To help keep your unit in good working order and avoid the need for <a href="//<?php echo $_SERVER['SERVER_NAME']; ?>/ac-repair-or-replacement-winnipeg" data-track-event="click" data-track-action="internal_link_clicked">repairs or a replacement</a>, here are seven tasks that should be part of your routine air conditioner maintenance.<br><br></p><p><span style="font-weight: bold;">1. Clean the unit</span></p><p>Dirt and debris can accumulate on the coils, which reduces efficiency and increases stress on the machine’s mechanical components. Start by cleaning the outdoor unit, including the condenser coil, followed by the evaporator coil in the indoor system.<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">2. Check the compressor</span></p><p>If the compressor doesn’t have enough refrigerant, it might start to work too hard. This will reduce the system’s overall efficiency and longevity. Make sure the refrigerant tubes aren’t blocked or leaking.<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">3. Inspect the drainage system</span></p><p>The condensation drain line and drain pan must be in good shape and unobstructed. Otherwise, excess moisture can get trapped in the unit or inside the house. This can lead to malfunctions and mould growth.&nbsp;<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">4. Check the fans</span></p><p>Most central air systems have two fans. The one in the outdoor unit pulls air through the coil fins, and the indoor blower fan moves air through the ducts. A problem with either of these fans can cause the entire system to malfunction.&nbsp;<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">5. Lubricate the components</span></p><p>While newer units are sealed, older models often have ports near the fan motors and other moving parts. These openings allow you to apply a lubricant periodically. Check your owner’s manual to find out if your unit requires this type of maintenance.<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">6. Inspect the controls</span></p><p>Electrical issues with an air conditioner can be serious. Make sure all the electrical components, from the controls to the power supply, are in good condition and performing correctly.<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">7. Change the filters</span></p><p>Dirt in the filters blocks air flow and makes the system needlessly work harder, so check them monthly. They’ll either need to be cleaned or changed, depending on your unit. Clean filters can reduce your air conditioning costs by up to 15 per cent.<br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">Air Conditioner Repair in Winnipeg<br></span>While these maintenance steps are important, the best way to ensure the proper function and longevity of your air conditioner is to have it <a href="//<?php echo $_SERVER['SERVER_NAME']; ?>/ac-service-company-winnipeg" data-track-event="click" data-track-action="internal_link_clicked">serviced by a professional</a>. Whether you need to have your unit repaired or replaced, <a href="/" data-track-event="click" data-track-action="internal_link_clicked">East Side Ventilation</a> can help. We carry a wide range of products to meet your heating and air conditioning needs. If you live in the Winnipeg area, <a href="/winnipeg-hvac-company-contact" data-track-event="click" data-track-action="internal_link_clicked">contact us</a> today to learn more about our services.</p> </div>
